{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-bee2e09c1ed968e0", "type": "tool_result", "content": "<head><script>document.documentElement.classList.add('js');</script>  <title>[2607.12290v1] The Sound of Absence: Audio-Language Embedding Models Struggle with Negation</title>\n  <meta name=\"description\" content=\"Abstract page for arXiv paper 2607.12290v1: The Sound of Absence: Audio-Language Embedding Models Struggle with Negation\"><meta property=\"og:type\" content=\"website\" />\n<meta property=\"og:title\" content=\"The Sound of Absence: Audio-Language Embedding Models Struggle with Negation\" />\n<meta name=\"twitter:title\" content=\"The Sound of Absence: Audio-Language Embedding Models Struggle...\"/>\n  <script src=\"/static/browse/0.3.4/js/cite.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script><meta name=\"citation_title\" content=\"The Sound of Absence: Audio-Language Embedding Models Struggle with Negation\" /><meta name=\"citation_author\" content=\"Kuan, Chun-Yi\" /><meta name=\"citation_author\" content=\"Lee, Hung-yi\" /><meta name=\"citation_date\" content=\"2026/07/14\" /><meta name=\"citation_online_date\" content=\"2026/07/14\" /><meta name=\"citation_pdf_url\" content=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.12290\" /><meta name=\"citation_arxiv_id\" content=\"2607.12290\" /><meta name=\"citation_abstract\" content=\"Audio-language embedding models such as CLAP are widely evaluated on matching present sound events, but rarely on negation. We show this affirmation-only evaluation hides a key limitation: these models fail to encode negated sound concepts, mapping affirmative and negated captions to nearly identical representations. To expose this blind spot, we introduce NegEval-Audio, a framework that converts existing datasets into two negation-aware tasks, Retrieval-Neg and Multiple-Choice Negation (MCQ-Neg), to probe whether models distinguish present from absent events. On AudioCaps and Clotho, performance degrades sharply under negation, with negation-type MCQ accuracy falling far below chance, and the failure persists even for a recent multimodal LLM-based embedding model. While a training-free steering method improves MCQ-Neg, it yields marginal gains for Retrieval-Neg. This indicates that affirmation bias is a fundamental flaw in the representation geometry, necessitating explicit negation-aware training objectives.\" />\n        placeholder=\"Search papers by title, author, abstract, or ID...\">\n        dc:title=\"The Sound of Absence: Audio-Language Embedding Models Struggle with Negation\"\n    <h1 class=\"title mathjax\"><span class=\"descriptor\">Title:</span>The Sound of Absence: Audio-Language Embedding Models Struggle with Negation</h1>\n    <div class=\"authors\"><span class=\"descriptor\">Authors:</span><a href=\"https://arxiv.org/search/eess?searchtype=author&amp;query=Kuan,+C\" rel=\"nofollow\">Chun-Yi Kuan</a>, <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/search/eess?searchtype=author&amp;query=Lee,+H\" rel=\"nofollow\">Hung-yi Lee</a></div>            <div id=\"download-button-info\" hidden>View a PDF of the paper titled The Sound of Absence: Audio-Language Embedding Models Struggle with Negation, by Chun-Yi Kuan and 1 other authors</div>\n    <blockquote class=\"abstract mathjax\">\n            <span class=\"descriptor\">Abstract:</span>Audio-language embedding models such as CLAP are widely evaluated on matching present sound events, but rarely on negation. We show this affirmation-only evaluation hides a key limitation: these models fail to encode negated sound concepts, mapping affirmative and negated captions to nearly identical representations. To expose this blind spot, we introduce NegEval-Audio, a framework that converts existing datasets into two negation-aware tasks, Retrieval-Neg and Multiple-Choice Negation (MCQ-Neg), to probe whether models distinguish present from absent events. On AudioCaps and Clotho, performance degrades sharply under negation, with negation-type MCQ accuracy falling far below chance, and the failure persists even for a recent multimodal LLM-based embedding model. While a training-free steering method improves MCQ-Neg, it yields marginal gains for Retrieval-Neg. This indicates that affirmation bias is a fundamental flaw in the representation geometry, necessitating explicit negation-aware training objectives.\n          <td class=\"tablecell arxivdoi\">              <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2607.12290\" id=\"arxiv-doi-link\">https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2607.12290</a><div class=\"button-and-tooltip\">\n                <span class=\"left-corner\"></span>                  arXiv-issued DOI via DataCite (pending registration)</div>\nView a PDF of the paper titled The Sound of Absence: Audio-Language Embedding Models Struggle with Negation, by Chun-Yi Kuan and 1 other authors</div><li><a href=\"/pdf/2607.12290v1\" aria-describedby=\"download-button-info\" accesskey=\"f\" class=\"abs-button download-pdf\">View PDF</a></li><li><a href=\"https://arxiv.org/html/2607.12290v1\" class=\"abs-button\" id=\"latexml-download-link\">HTML (experimental)</a></li><li><a href=\"/src/2607.12290v1\" class=\"abs-button download-eprint\">TeX Source\n      <div class=\"abs-license\"><a href=\"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/\" title=\"Rights to this article\">view license</a></div>\n         accesskey=\"p\" title=\"previous in eess.AS (accesskey p)\" rel=\"nofollow\">&lt;&nbsp;prev</a>\n         title=\"next in eess.AS (accesskey n)\"  rel=\"nofollow\">next&nbsp;&gt;</a>\n        <div class='bib-modal-title'>\n     title=\"Bookmark on BibSonomy\">\n  <a class=\"abs-button abs-button-grey abs-button-small\" href=\"https://reddit.com/submit?url=https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.12290&amp;title=The Sound of Absence: Audio-Language Embedding Models Struggle with Negation\"", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "c410d160-d037-48ab-83c3-103881cdf968", "uuid": "e17b31bd-04a2-412e-aea8-8366d73fc49f", "timestamp": "2026-07-15T11:13:17.454Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "<head><script>document.documentElement.classList.add('js');</script>  <title>[2607.12290v1] The Sound of Absence: Audio-Language Embedding Models Struggle with Negation</title>\n  <meta name=\"description\" content=\"Abstract page for arXiv paper 2607.12290v1: The Sound of Absence: Audio-Language Embedding Models Struggle with Negation\"><meta property=\"og:type\" content=\"website\" />\n<meta property=\"og:title\" content=\"The Sound of Absence: Audio-Language Embedding Models Struggle with Negation\" />\n<meta name=\"twitter:title\" content=\"The Sound of Absence: Audio-Language Embedding Models Struggle...\"/>\n  <script src=\"/static/browse/0.3.4/js/cite.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script><meta name=\"citation_title\" content=\"The Sound of Absence: Audio-Language Embedding Models Struggle with Negation\" /><meta name=\"citation_author\" content=\"Kuan, Chun-Yi\" /><meta name=\"citation_author\" content=\"Lee, Hung-yi\" /><meta name=\"citation_date\" content=\"2026/07/14\" /><meta name=\"citation_online_date\" content=\"2026/07/14\" /><meta name=\"citation_pdf_url\" content=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.12290\" /><meta name=\"citation_arxiv_id\" content=\"2607.12290\" /><meta name=\"citation_abstract\" content=\"Audio-language embedding models such as CLAP are widely evaluated on matching present sound events, but rarely on negation. We show this affirmation-only evaluation hides a key limitation: these models fail to encode negated sound concepts, mapping affirmative and negated captions to nearly identical representations. To expose this blind spot, we introduce NegEval-Audio, a framework that converts existing datasets into two negation-aware tasks, Retrieval-Neg and Multiple-Choice Negation (MCQ-Neg), to probe whether models distinguish present from absent events. On AudioCaps and Clotho, performance degrades sharply under negation, with negation-type MCQ accuracy falling far below chance, and the failure persists even for a recent multimodal LLM-based embedding model. While a training-free steering method improves MCQ-Neg, it yields marginal gains for Retrieval-Neg. This indicates that affirmation bias is a fundamental flaw in the representation geometry, necessitating explicit negation-aware training objectives.\" />\n        placeholder=\"Search papers by title, author, abstract, or ID...\">\n        dc:title=\"The Sound of Absence: Audio-Language Embedding Models Struggle with Negation\"\n    <h1 class=\"title mathjax\"><span class=\"descriptor\">Title:</span>The Sound of Absence: Audio-Language Embedding Models Struggle with Negation</h1>\n    <div class=\"authors\"><span class=\"descriptor\">Authors:</span><a href=\"https://arxiv.org/search/eess?searchtype=author&amp;query=Kuan,+C\" rel=\"nofollow\">Chun-Yi Kuan</a>, <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/search/eess?searchtype=author&amp;query=Lee,+H\" rel=\"nofollow\">Hung-yi Lee</a></div>            <div id=\"download-button-info\" hidden>View a PDF of the paper titled The Sound of Absence: Audio-Language Embedding Models Struggle with Negation, by Chun-Yi Kuan and 1 other authors</div>\n    <blockquote class=\"abstract mathjax\">\n            <span class=\"descriptor\">Abstract:</span>Audio-language embedding models such as CLAP are widely evaluated on matching present sound events, but rarely on negation. We show this affirmation-only evaluation hides a key limitation: these models fail to encode negated sound concepts, mapping affirmative and negated captions to nearly identical representations. To expose this blind spot, we introduce NegEval-Audio, a framework that converts existing datasets into two negation-aware tasks, Retrieval-Neg and Multiple-Choice Negation (MCQ-Neg), to probe whether models distinguish present from absent events. On AudioCaps and Clotho, performance degrades sharply under negation, with negation-type MCQ accuracy falling far below chance, and the failure persists even for a recent multimodal LLM-based embedding model. While a training-free steering method improves MCQ-Neg, it yields marginal gains for Retrieval-Neg. This indicates that affirmation bias is a fundamental flaw in the representation geometry, necessitating explicit negation-aware training objectives.\n          <td class=\"tablecell arxivdoi\">              <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2607.12290\" id=\"arxiv-doi-link\">https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2607.12290</a><div class=\"button-and-tooltip\">\n                <span class=\"left-corner\"></span>                  arXiv-issued DOI via DataCite (pending registration)</div>\nView a PDF of the paper titled The Sound of Absence: Audio-Language Embedding Models Struggle with Negation, by Chun-Yi Kuan and 1 other authors</div><li><a href=\"/pdf/2607.12290v1\" aria-describedby=\"download-button-info\" accesskey=\"f\" class=\"abs-button download-pdf\">View PDF</a></li><li><a href=\"https://arxiv.org/html/2607.12290v1\" class=\"abs-button\" id=\"latexml-download-link\">HTML (experimental)</a></li><li><a href=\"/src/2607.12290v1\" class=\"abs-button download-eprint\">TeX Source\n      <div class=\"abs-license\"><a href=\"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/\" title=\"Rights to this article\">view license</a></div>\n         accesskey=\"p\" title=\"previous in eess.AS (accesskey p)\" rel=\"nofollow\">&lt;&nbsp;prev</a>\n         title=\"next in eess.AS (accesskey n)\"  rel=\"nofollow\">next&nbsp;&gt;</a>\n        <div class='bib-modal-title'>\n     title=\"Bookmark on BibSonomy\">\n  <a class=\"abs-button abs-button-grey abs-button-small\" href=\"https://reddit.com/submit?url=https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.12290&amp;title=The Sound of Absence: Audio-Language Embedding Models Struggle with Negation\"", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
