 preprint arXiv:2207.00221.\n1732\t\n1733\tCited by: §II-B.\n1734\t\n1735\t- \n1736\t[75]\n1737\tL. Zhou, H. Jiang, J. Li, T. Wang, and H. Li (2026)\n1738\t\n1739\tEmoShift: lightweight activation steering for enhanced emotion-aware speech synthesis.\n1740\t\n1741\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2601.22873.\n1742\t\n1743\tCited by: §IV.\n1744\t\n1745\t## \n1746\tAppendix A Controlled Diagnosis of Text-Side Negation Handling\n1747\t\n1748\tThis appendix provides the implementation details and full results for the\n1749\tcontrolled diagnosis in Section VI-D. The main paper reports the\n1750\tresults averaged over five LAION-CLAP [64] checkpoints; here, we additionally include\n1751\tthe LLM-based embedding model WAVE-7B [56].\n1752\t\n1753\t### \n1754\tA-A Controlled setup\n1755\t\n1756\tWe construct 1,000 controlled target–distractor pairs from ESC-50\n1757\t[52].\n1758\tEach item contains two positive sound events,\n1759\tp1p_{1} and p2p_{2}, and one designated negated concept YY. The two positive\n1760\tevents are concatenated into a 10 s base clip.\n1761\tWe then overlay either YY or a\n1762\tfiller event FF at the same onset and gain:\n1763\t\n1764\t- \n1765\t• \n1766\t\n1767\ttarget: the base clip with filler FF, but without YY;\n1768\t\n1769\t- \n1770\t• \n1771\t\n1772\tdistractor: the same base clip with YY.\n1773\t\n1774\tThe filler FF is matched to YY in coarse ESC-50 category and loudness.\n1775\tTherefore, the target and distractor differ only in whether the overlaid event\n1776\tis FF or the negated concept YY.\n1777\tSound presence is known by construction and does not require ALLM verification.\n1778\tFor each item, we construct a negated query, “PP, with no YY”, its\n1779\taffirmative counterpart, “PP, with YY”, and the oracle description “PP”, where PP contains the two positive concepts.\n1780\tWe additionally construct the following deterministic text references:\n1781\t\n1782\t- \n1783\t• \n1784\t\n1785\ta meaning-preserving paraphrase, obtained by reversing the\n1786\tpositive-concept order and replacing “no” with “without”;\n1787\t\n1788\t- \n1789\t• \n1790\t\n1791\ta content-swap reference, obtained by replacing one positive\n1792\tconcept;\n1793\t\n1794\t- \n1795\t• \n1796\t\n1797\tan unrelated query from another item;\n1798\t\n1799\t- \n1800\t• \n1801\t\n1802\tthree scope variants, which negate each of\n1803\t{p1,p2,Y}\\{p_{1},p_{2},Y\\} in turn;\n1804\t\n1805\t- \n1806\t• \n1807\t\n1808\ta bag-of-concepts reference containing only the three concept\n1809\tphrases.\n1810\t\n1811\tFor WAVE-7B, an instruction-aware MLLM embedding model, audio embeddings are conditioned on a text instruction.\n1812\tWe use “Please describe the audio.” as the instruction.\n1813\tAll embeddings are L2L_{2}-normalized before computing\n1814\tcosine similarity.\n1815\t\n1816\t### \n1817\tA-B Metrics\n1818\t\n1819\tLet qq be the negated-query embedding, and let\n1820\ttafft_{\\mathrm{aff}}, tparat_{\\mathrm{para}}, tswapt_{\\mathrm{swap}}, and\n1821\ttunrelt_{\\mathrm{unrel}} denote the affirmative, paraphrase, content-swap, and\n1822\tunrelated references, respectively.\n1823\t\n1824\tPolarity sensitivity.\n1825\tWe report\n1826\t\n1827\tnormalized affinity\n1828\t=s​(q,taff)−s​(q,tunrel)s​(q,tpara)−s​(q,tunrel),\\displaystyle=\\frac{s(q,t_{\\mathrm{aff}})-s(q,t_{\\mathrm{unrel}})}{s(q,t_{\\mathrm{para}})-s(q,t_{\\mathrm{unrel}})},\n1829\t\n1830\t(1)\n1831\t\n1832\tpolarity/content\\displaystyle\\text{polarity}/\\text{content}\n1833\t=1−s​(q,taff)1−s​(q,tswap).\\displaystyle=\\frac{1-s(q,t_{\\mathrm{aff}})}{1-s(q,t_{\\mathrm{swap}})}.\n1834\t\n1835\t(2)\n1836\t\n1837\tA normalized affinity near or above 11 means that the truth-opposite\n1838\taffirmative is as close to the query as its meaning-preserving paraphrase. A\n1839\tpolarity/content ratio below 11 means that changing polarity moves the\n1840\tembedding less than replacing one sound concept.\n1841\t\n1842\tNegation scope.\n1843\tFor the three scope variants {v1,v2,v3}\\{v_{1},v_{2},v_{3}\\}, we compute\n1844\t\n1845\tscope-perm=meani<j​s​(vi,vj).\\text{scope-perm}=\\mathrm{mean}_{i<j}\\,s(v_{i},v_{j}).\n1846\t\n1847\tWe compare this value with the content-swap similarity\n1848\ts​(q,tswap)s(q,t_{\\mathrm{swap}}) and the bag-of-concepts similarity\n1849\ts​(q,tbag)s(q,t_{\\mathrm{bag}}). High scope-permutation and bag-of-concepts\n1850\tsimilarities indicate weak encoding of which concept is negated.\n1851\t\n1852\tAudio-retrieval bridge.\n1853\tFor each item, we define\n1854\t\n1855\tm​(q)=s​(q,adist)−s​(q,atgt).m(q)=s(q,a_{\\mathrm{dist}})-s(q,a_{\\mathrm{tgt}}).\n1856\t\n1857\tA positive margin indicates that the query prefers the distractor containing\n1858\tthe negated concept. We report the mean margins for the negated and affirmative\n1859\tqueries, together with their item-level correlation.\n1860\t\n1861\t### \n1862\tA-C Full results\n1863\t\n1864\tTABLE V: \n1865\tControlled text-side negation diagnosis for the mean over five LAION-CLAP\n1866\tcheckpoints and WAVE-7B.\n1867\t\n1868\tDiagnostic\n1869\t\n1870\tCLAP\n1871\tWAVE-7B\n1872\t\n1873\tPolarity sensitivity\n1874\t\n1875\tNormalized affinity to affirmative text\n1876\t\n1877\t1.07\n1878\t1.05\n1879\t\n1880\tPolarity change / content swap\n1881\t\n1882\t0.30\n1883\t0.12\n1884\t\n1885\tNegation scope\n1886\t\n1887\tScope-permutation similarity\n1888\t\n1889\t0.70\n1890\t0.90\n1891\t\n1892\tContent-swap similarity\n1893\t\n1894\t0.58\n1895\t0.70\n1896\t\n1897\tBag-of-concepts similarity\n1898\t\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "c410d160-d037-48ab-83c3-103881cdf968", "uuid": "1e990ac3-b403-4aed-8e5b-c3bbff57c6a2", "timestamp": "2026-07-15T11:20:34.866Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_2607_text.txt", "content": "[63]\nH. Wu, X. Chen, Y. Lin, K. Chang, H. Chung, A. H. Liu, and H. Lee (2024)\n\nTowards audio language modeling–an overview.\n\narXiv preprint arXiv:2402.13236.\n\nCited by: §I.\n\n- \n[64]\nY. Wu, K. Chen, T. Zhang, Y. Hui, T. Berg-Kirkpatrick, and S. Dubnov (2023)\n\nLarge-scale contrastive language-audio pretraining with feature fusion and keyword-to-caption augmentation.\n\nIn ICASSP 2023-2023 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP),\n\n pp. 1–5.\n\nCited by: Appendix A,\n§I,\n§II-A,\nTABLE I,\nTABLE II,\nTABLE III,\n§V.\n\n- \n[65]\nT. Xie, S. Yang, C. Li, D. Yu, and L. Liu (2025)\n\nEmoSteer-tts: fine-grained and training-free emotion-controllable text-to-speech via activation steering.\n\narXiv preprint arXiv:2508.03543.\n\nCited by: §IV.\n\n- \n[66]\nJ. Xu, Z. Guo, J. He, H. Hu, T. He, S. Bai, K. Chen, J. Wang, Y. Fan, K. Dang, et al. (2025)\n\nQwen2.5-omni technical report.\n\narXiv preprint arXiv:2503.20215.\n\nCited by: §I,\n§V.\n\n- \n[67]\nJ. Xu (2026)\n\nOmni-negclip: enhancing clip with front-layer contrastive fine-tuning for comprehensive negation understanding.\n\nIn Proceedings of the IEEE/CVF Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition,\n\n pp. 9392–9401.\n\nCited by: §VII.\n\n- \n[68]\nC. Yang, Y. Fu, C. Li, Y. Lin, Y. Lin, W. Chen, H. L. Chung, C. Kuan, W. Huang, K. Lu, et al. (2024)\n\nBuilding a taiwanese mandarin spoken language model: a first attempt.\n\narXiv preprint arXiv:2411.07111.\n\nCited by: §I.\n\n- \n[69]\nS. Yang, M. Tu, A. T. Liu, X. Qu, H. Lee, L. Lu, Y. Wang, and Y. Wu (2025)\n\nParaS2S: benchmarking and aligning spoken language models for paralinguistic-aware speech-to-speech interaction.\n\narXiv preprint arXiv:2511.08723.\n\nCited by: §V.\n\n- \n[70]\nZ. Ye, R. Huang, Y. Ren, Z. Jiang, J. Liu, J. He, X. Yin, and Z. Zhao (2023)\n\nClapspeech: learning prosody from text context with contrastive language-audio pre-training.\n\nIn Proceedings of the 61st Annual Meeting of the Association for Computational Linguistics (Volume 1: Long Papers),\n\n pp. 9317–9331.\n\nCited by: §I,\n§II-A.\n\n- \n[71]\nY. Yuan, Z. Chen, X. Liu, H. Liu, X. Xu, D. Jia, Y. Chen, M. D. Plumbley, and W. Wang (2024)\n\nT-clap: temporal-enhanced contrastive language-audio pretraining.\n\nIn 2024 IEEE 34th International Workshop on Machine Learning for Signal Processing (MLSP),\n\n pp. 1–6.\n\nCited by: §I,\n§II-A.\n\n- \n[72]\nM. Yuksekgonul, F. Bianchi, P. Kalluri, D. Jurafsky, and J. Zou (2023)\n\nWhen and why vision-language models behave like bags-of-words, and what to do about it?.\n\nIn The Eleventh International Conference on Learning Representations,\n\nCited by: §II-B.\n\n- \n[73]\nY. Zhang, Y. Su, Y. Liu, and S. Yeung-Levy (2025)\n\nNegVQA: can vision language models understand negation?.\n\narXiv preprint arXiv:2505.22946.\n\nCited by: §II-B.\n\n- \n[74]\nT. Zhao, T. Zhang, M. Zhu, H. Shen, K. Lee, X. Lu, and J. Yin (2022)\n\nVl-checklist: evaluating pre-trained vision-language models with objects, attributes and relations.\n\narXiv preprint arXiv:2207.00221.\n\nCited by: §II-B.\n\n- \n[75]\nL. Zhou, H. Jiang, J. Li, T. Wang, and H. Li (2026)\n\nEmoShift: lightweight activation steering for enhanced emotion-aware speech synthesis.\n\narXiv preprint arXiv:2601.22873.\n\nCited by: §IV.\n\n## \nAppendix A Controlled Diagnosis of Text-Side Negation Handling\n\nThis appendix provides the implementation details and full results for the\ncontrolled diagnosis in Section VI-D. The main paper reports the\nresults averaged over five LAION-CLAP [64] checkpoints; here, we additionally include\nthe LLM-based embedding model WAVE-7B [56].\n\n### \nA-A Controlled setup\n\nWe construct 1,000 controlled target–distractor pairs from ESC-50\n[52].\nEach item contains two positive sound events,\np1p_{1} and p2p_{2}, and one designated negated concept YY. The two positive\nevents are concatenated into a 10 s base clip.\nWe then overlay either YY or a\nfiller event FF at the same onset and gain:\n\n- \n• \n\ntarget: the base clip with filler FF, but without YY;\n\n- \n• \n\ndistractor: the same base clip with YY.\n\nThe filler FF is matched to YY in coarse ESC-50 category and loudness.\nTherefore, the target and distractor differ only in whether the overlaid event\nis FF or the negated concept YY.\nSound presence is known by construction and does not require ALLM verification.\nFor each item, we construct a negated query, “PP, with no YY”, its\naffirmative counterpart, “PP, with YY”, and the oracle description “PP”, where PP contains the two positive concepts.\nWe additionally construct the following deterministic text references:\n\n- \n• \n\na meaning-preserving paraphrase, obtained by reversing the\npositive-concept order and replacing “no” with “without”;\n\n- \n• \n\na content-swap reference, obtained by replacing one positive\nconcept;\n\n- \n• \n\nan unrelated query from another item;\n\n- \n• \n\nthree scope variants, which negate each of\n{p1,p2,Y}\\{p_{1},p_{2},Y\\} in turn;\n\n- \n• \n\na bag-of-concepts reference containing only the three concept\nphrases.\n\nFor WAVE-7B, an instruction-aware MLLM embedding model, audio embeddings are conditioned on a text instruction.\nWe use “Please describe the audio.” as the instruction.\nAll embeddings are L2L_{2}-normalized before computing\ncosine similarity.\n\n### \nA-B Metrics\n\nLet qq be the negated-query embedding, and let\ntafft_{\\mathrm{aff}}, tparat_{\\mathrm{para}}, tswapt_{\\mathrm{swap}}, and\ntunrelt_{\\mathrm{unrel}} denote the affirmative, paraphrase, content-swap, and\nunrelated references, respectively.\n\nPolarity sensitivity.\nWe report\n\nnormalized affinity\n=s​(q,taff)−s​(q,tunrel)s​(q,tpara)−s​(q,tunrel),\\displaystyle=\\frac{s(q,t_{\\mathrm{aff}})-s(q,t_{\\mathrm{unrel}})}{s(q,t_{\\mathrm{para}})-s(q,t_{\\mathrm{unrel}})},\n\n(1)\n\npolarity/content\\displaystyle\\text{polarity}/\\text{content}\n=1−s​(q,taff)1−s​(q,tswap).\\displaystyle=\\frac{1-s(q,t_{\\mathrm{aff}})}{1-s(q,t_{\\mathrm{swap}})}.\n\n(2)\n\nA normalized affinity near or above 11 means that the truth-opposite\naffirmative is as close to the query as its meaning-preserving paraphrase. A\npolarity/content ratio below 11 means that changing polarity moves the\nembedding less than replacing one sound concept.\n\nNegation scope.\nFor the three scope variants {v1,v2,v3}\\{v_{1},v_{2},v_{3}\\}, we compute\n\nscope-perm=meani<j​s​(vi,vj).\\text{scope-perm}=\\mathrm{mean}_{i<j}\\,s(v_{i},v_{j}).\n\nWe compare this value with the content-swap similarity\ns​(q,tswap)s(q,t_{\\mathrm{swap}}) and the bag-of-concepts similarity\ns​(q,tbag)s(q,t_{\\mathrm{bag}}). High scope-permutation and bag-of-concepts\nsimilarities indicate weak encoding of which concept is negated.\n\nAudio-retrieval bridge.\nFor each item, we define\n\nm​(q)=s​(q,adist)−s​(q,atgt).m(q)=s(q,a_{\\mathrm{dist}})-s(q,a_{\\mathrm{tgt}}).\n\nA positive margin indicates that the query prefers the distractor containing\nthe negated concept. We report the mean margins for the negated and affirmative\nqueries, together with their item-level correlation.\n\n### \nA-C Full results\n\nTABLE V: \nControlled text-side negation diagnosis for the mean over five LAION-CLAP\ncheckpoints and WAVE-7B.\n\nDiagnostic\n\nCLAP\nWAVE-7B\n\nPolarity sensitivity\n\nNormalized affinity to affirmative text\n\n1.07\n1.05\n\nPolarity change / content swap\n\n0.30\n0.12\n\nNegation scope\n\nScope-permutation similarity\n\n0.70\n0.90\n\nContent-swap similarity\n\n0.58\n0.70\n\nBag-of-concepts similarity\n", "numLines": 300, "startLine": 1599, "totalLines": 2695}}}
