{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-b4a6e9a68f71ec53", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1898\t\n1899\t0.82\n1900\t0.91\n1901\t\n1902\tAudio-retrieval bridge\n1903\t\n1904\tNegated–affirmative margin correlation\n1905\t\n1906\t0.76\n1907\t0.94\n1908\t\n1909\tNegated-query margin\n1910\t\n1911\t+0.018\n1912\t+0.016\n1913\t\n1914\tAffirmative-query margin\n1915\t\n1916\t+0.072\n1917\t+0.022\n1918\t\n1919\tTable V reveals three consistent patterns\n1920\tacross both model families.\n1921\t\n1922\tNegation is only a weak perturbation.\n1923\tThe affirmative counterpart is at least as close to the negated query as the\n1924\tmeaning-preserving paraphrase, with normalized affinities of 1.071.07 for CLAP\n1925\tand 1.051.05 for WAVE-7B.\n1926\tPolarity changes are also substantially smaller than\n1927\tcontent swaps, particularly for WAVE-7B, whose polarity/content ratio is only\n1928\t0.120.12. Thus, changing whether a concept is affirmed or negated affects the\n1929\tembedding much less than changing the concept itself.\n1930\t\n1931\tNegation is weakly bound to the intended concept.\n1932\tFor CLAP, the scope-permutation similarity (0.700.70) exceeds the content-swap\n1933\tsimilarity (0.580.58), while the bag-of-concepts similarity remains high\n1934\t(0.820.82). The pattern is even stronger for WAVE-7B: its scope variants have a\n1935\tsimilarity of 0.900.90, close to its bag-of-concepts similarity of 0.910.91.\n1936\tThese results indicate that the representations preserve which sound concepts\n1937\tare mentioned more strongly than which concept is negated.\n1938\t\n1939\tThe text-side failure carries over to audio ranking.\n1940\tNegated and affirmative queries induce strongly correlated audio margins\n1941\t(0.760.76 for CLAP and 0.940.94 for WAVE-7B). Moreover, the negated-query margins\n1942\tremain positive (+0.018+0.018 and +0.016+0.016, respectively), indicating continued\n1943\tpreference for the audio containing the forbidden concept. Negated queries\n1944\ttherefore behave like attenuated affirmative queries rather than reversing the\n1945\tranking toward the target audio.\n1946\t\n1947\tOverall takeaway.\n1948\tAcross both model families, negation is represented as a weak modifier of\n1949\tmentioned concepts rather than an exclusion operator. This behavior persists\n1950\tfrom text representations to cross-modal audio ranking and is, on several\n1951\tmeasures, even more pronounced for WAVE-7B.\n1952\t\n1953\t## \n1954\tAppendix B Full λ\\lambda-Sweep for Training-Free Steering\n1955\t\n1956\tTABLE VI: \n1957\tRetrieval-Neg (R@5) versus steering strength λ\\lambda on AudioCaps test [32].\n1958\tPer-model best results are shown in bold, the value used in the main paper\n1959\t(λ=0.2\\lambda=0.2) is underlined, and gray cells denote the no-steering baseline\n1960\t(λ=0\\lambda=0).\n1961\t\n1962\tModel\n1963\t\n1964\t\\cellcolorlightgray0\n1965\t\n1966\t0.1\n1967\t0.2\n1968\t0.3\n1969\t0.5\n1970\t0.7\n1971\t1\n1972\t1.5\n1973\t2\n1974\t3\n1975\t5\n1976\t8\n1977\t\n1978\tLAION-CLAP\n1979\t\n1980\t– 630k-audioset-best\n1981\t\n1982\t\\cellcolorlightgray60.3\n1983\t\n1984\t61.5\n1985\t61.8\n1986\t60.8\n1987\t55.4\n1988\t48.6\n1989\t36.8\n1990\t20.9\n1991\t10.8\n1992\t4.2\n1993\t1.9\n1994\t0.9\n1995\t\n1996\t– 630k-best\n1997\t\n1998\t\\cellcolorlightgray59.1\n1999\t\n2000\t59.5\n2001\t58.5\n2002\t57.3\n2003\t51.1\n2004\t43.0\n2005\t27.0\n2006\t12.8\n2007\t6.5\n2008\t2.4\n2009\t0.4\n2010\t0.1\n2011\t\n2012\t– music-audioset\n2013\t\n2014\t\\cellcolorlightgray57.0\n2015\t\n2016\t57.2\n2017\t57.3\n2018\t55.9\n2019\t50.8\n2020\t44.8\n2021\t33.4\n2022\t18.7\n2023\t10.4\n2024\t3.8\n2025\t2.0\n2026\t0.8\n2027\t\n2028\t– music-speech-audioset\n2029\t\n2030\t\\cellcolorlightgray57.9\n2031\t\n2032\t58.4\n2033\t58.6\n2034\t59.0\n2035\t54.4\n2036\t49.1\n2037\t39.0\n2038\t21.7\n2039\t13.5\n2040\t6.0\n2041\t2.8\n2042\t1.2\n2043\t\n2044\t– music-speech\n2045\t\n2046\t\\cellcolorlight